## 7. Summary Table: Reasons for Competing Innovation System Classifications  

| Reason                          | Explanation                                                                                      | Source(s)                                      |
|--------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| Multidimensionality             | Innovation systems span geographic, sectoral, and temporal dimensions                          | Carlsson et al., 2002; Wikipedia, 2024         |
| Analytical Level Variation      | Different research or policy questions require different system boundaries and focuses         | Carlsson et al., 2002; ResearchGate, 2007      |
| Boundary Ambiguity              | Overlapping and fuzzy boundaries due to complex actor interactions and classifications          | Porter, 1998; Carlsson et al., 2002             |
| Dynamic Nature                 | Innovation systems evolve over time, complicating static classification                        | Carlsson et al., 2002                           |
| Historical and Institutional Context | Different countries and regions have unique institutional setups influencing system design   | Freeman, 2002; Viotti, 1997                      |
| Conceptual Variations           | Differing definitions of innovation system vs. innovation ecosystem and narrow vs. broad views | Granstrand & Holgersson, 2020; Lundvall, 1992  |
| Purpose-Driven Frameworks       | Frameworks tailored to specific policy, economic, or technological objectives                   | Breschi & Malerba, 1997; Decision-Making Solutions, 2024 |

---

## 8. Conclusion  

Competing classifications of innovation systems arise from the inherent complexity and multidimensionality of innovation processes, the diversity of analytical purposes, and the evolving nature of the systems themselves. The absence of a universally accepted definition or boundary reflects the dynamic interplay of technological, institutional, geographic, and temporal factors. Furthermore, historical legacies and policy contexts shape how innovation systems are conceptualized in different settings. Rather than viewing competing classifications as a weakness, they represent complementary perspectives that enrich understanding and enable tailored approaches to studying and fostering innovation.

For researchers and policymakers, recognizing the reasons behind these competing classifications is crucial for selecting appropriate frameworks that align with specific objectives and contexts. Future work should focus on integrating these perspectives and developing flexible, multi-level frameworks that accommodate the dynamic and systemic nature of innovation.

